06008nam a22006855i 9780822376729DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223767297 a10.1515/97808223767292doi  a(DE-B1597)553279  a(OCoLC)870971335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aMestizo Genomics :bRace Mixture, Nation, and Science in Latin America /cRicardo Ventura Santos, Eduardo Restrepo, Carlos López Beltrán, Peter Wade. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b4 photos, 2 tables, 6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: Genomics, Race Mixture, and Nation in Latin America -- tpart I. history and context -- t1 From Degeneration to Meeting Point -- t2 Nation and Difference in the Genetic Imagination of Colombia -- t3 Negotiating the Mexican Mestizo -- tpart II. laboratory case studies -- t4 "The Charrua Are Alive" -- t5 The Travels of Humans, Categories, and Other Genetic Products -- t6 Laboratory Life of the Mexican Mestizo -- t7 Social Categories and Laboratory Practices in Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico -- tCONCLUSION: Race, Multiculturalism, and Genomics in Latin America -- tAppendix: Methods and Context -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn genetics laboratories in Latin America, scientists have been mapping the genomes of local populations, seeking to locate the genetic basis of complex diseases and to trace population histories. As part of their work, geneticists often calculate the European, African, and Amerindian genetic ancestry of populations. Some researchers explicitly connect their findings to questions of national identity and racial and ethnic difference, bringing their research to bear on issues of politics and identity.Drawing on ethnographic research in Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico, the contributors to Mestizo Genomics explore how the concepts of race, ethnicity, nation, and gender enter into and are affected by genomic research. In Latin America, national identities are often based on ideas about mestizaje (race mixture), rather than racial division. Since mestizaje is said to involve relations between European men and indigenous or African women, gender is a key factor in Latin American genomics and in the analyses in this book. Also important are links between contemporary genomics and recent moves toward official multiculturalism in Brazil, Colombia, and Mexico. One of the first studies of its kind, Mestizo Genomics sheds new light on the interrelations between "race," identity, and genomics in Latin America.Contributors. Adriana Díaz del Castillo H., Roosbelinda Cárdenas, Vivette García Deister, Verlan Valle Gaspar Neto, Michael Kent, Carlos López Beltrán, María Fernanda Olarte Sierra, Eduardo Restrepo, Mariana Rios Sandoval, Ernesto Schwartz-Marín, Ricardo Ventura Santos, Peter Wade  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aDíaz del Castillo H, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez Beltrán, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRestrepo, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz-Marín, Ernesto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez Beltrán, Carlos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRios Sandoval, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSierra, María Fernanda Olarte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu